column4: <content>[recto] Wooded Landscape with 2 Hunters & 3 Dogs (Leegenhoek), panel, 38,5 x 55,5 cm. Landscape type - loo into forestglade - if by P.B.I - anticipating Coninxloo. Comparable to Prague landscape drawing of 1554 (used by Cock)(see Arndt), Drawing Berlin (Münz, N° 24 (recto & verso), but does not show any of the distant river valley view seen from above. Very close character landscape with bears (Brit.Mus. Münz, A 28 (J.B.?) Lugt [1927], Arndt [1972]: copy after P.B. and the engraving (Bast. 16): Pagus Nemorosus also without distant view. The foliage would agree with P.B.I, particularly the little impressionist leaves about the tree trunks, cf. Landscape with tower, San Diego (photograph Putnam 6c). But: the soil in broad horizontal brush strokes, the way the trees on the right are rooted in the ground the painterly form of the bushes tree trunk higher; [verso] centre and of the opening in tree trunk by left edge do not look like P.B. - The firm bottom right corner more like in Temptation Washington (though trees different); A beautiful picture - with the light breaking through the forest (cf. Rubenspatches of forest interess[ant]; The owl in the tree in left edge not very P.B. like - the dogs also different. Could this be J.B. after P.B.? or in the manner of P.B? Some of the trees too straight for P.B.; Brown of tree trunks dominates, (kind of underpainting like P.B. & Rubens); some impressionists green foliage (with impasto); man in centre with crimson jacket - white preparation, thin original panel covered by new cradling panel; left man has spear pointing down; right man has spear pointing upwards to left; 2 white and one brown [onleesbaar], brown goat at root of 3 rd curved tree from right ; 2nd tree from right: roots is pattern on surface, not growing out of soil, as P.B. Generally too much decorative pattern; Trees in the distance in middle-green, look like J.B.</content>

<part_of.title>Korte inhoud: Vermeldt studie relatie Pieter Bruegel de Oude en Jan Brueghel de Oude. Dankbetuiging dat Dr. Hahn hem het schilderij 'Forest Landscape with two Hunters and Three Dogs' liet zien. FG schrijft het werk toe aan Jan Brueghel's vroege periode. Staaft zijn argumentatie en kondigt een publicatie aan. Vraagt om meer foto's. [scan]</part_of.title>
